{"text": "2m+V(x)7! HL+HJ+HR (43.33)\n\nNamely, the unperturbed Hamiltonian is the sum of \"left\" and \"right\" segments, and the perturbation is the coupling\n\nat a \"junction\" that couples the two segments. This approach is most popular in STM applications. The question\n\narises how exactly to de\n\nne the 3 terms in the Hamiltonian. Apparently we have to selects a good basis that is\n\ncomposed of \"left\" and \"right\" eigenstates, and\n\ngure out how they are coupled at the junction. If the a \"point\n\ncontact\" junction is modelled as a delta function u\u000e(x\u0000x0) it is most natural to de\n\nne the \"left\" and \"right\"\n\neigenstates as '(x) = sin(k(x\u0000x0)), and one can show that the couplings at the energy of interest are given by the\n\nformula\n\nVR;L =1\n\n4m2u(@'R)(@'L) (43.34)\n\nwhere the derivative @is taken at the point x=x0. Bardeen has found that for a wide barrier it is possible to use\n\nthe following approximation:\n\nVR;L =1\n\n2m\u0002\n\n'R(@'L)\u0000(@'R)'L\u0003\n\nx0(43.35)\n\nwherex=x0is an arbitrary point within the barrier region. Note that the point-contact junction formula can be\n\nregarded as a limit of the latter. It should be clear that the implied matrix representation of the Hamiltonian is\n\nsomewhat problematic. E\u000bectively we consider a smaller Hilbert space, from which all the high lying states and the\n\nbarrier region are truncated. This is possibly not very important for transmission or decay rate calculation, but might\n\nbe disastrous for Lamb shift calculation. We note that within the matrix model analysis the Lamb shift is\n\n\u0001\u0019X\n\nkjVk;0j2\n\n\u000f0\u0000\u000fk= prefactor\u0002\u0000 (43.36)\n\nwhere the prefactor depends on the cuto\u000b of the dkintegration.", "embedding": [-0.00049051875, 0.0061587477, 0.02313351, 0.006765765, -0.0025493545, 0.002652685, 0.0023978257, -0.011036637, -0.057654306, 0.04874512, 0.038287748, -0.0002106183, -0.009950312, -0.032571662, -0.022702873, 0.04